# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this React + Vite portfolio project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 2.0.0
- Package added to dependencies in package.json
- Package-lock.json updated with new dependency tree

### 2. Code Integration
**Modified: `src/App.jsx`**
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/react'`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component to the AppInner component
- Placed after `<AIAssistant />` and before `<RouteScrollManager />` to ensure it's available across all routes

## Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Speed Insights documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), I used the React-specific integration:
- Used `@vercel/speed-insights/react` import path (correct for React/Vite projects)
- Added the component at the app root level to track performance across all routes
- The component is self-contained and requires no additional configuration

## Verification

✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
✅ No lint errors (no linter configured in project)
✅ No test failures (no tests configured in project)
✅ Build output: dist/assets/index-B01mRrq4.js (972.03 kB)

## Next Steps

After deploying to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard for your project
2. Visit the deployed site to generate initial performance data
3. Access Speed Insights metrics in your Vercel dashboard to monitor Web Vitals and page performance

## Notes

- The SpeedInsights component automatically tracks Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS)
- It sends performance data to Vercel's analytics endpoints at `/_vercel/speed-insights/*`
- No additional configuration is needed - the component works out of the box
- Performance tracking will only be active when deployed to Vercel (not in local development)
